{:title      "Writing Posts in Hiccup"
 :date       "2024-01-15"
 :categories ["clojure" "meta"]
 :summary    "How to write blog posts using Hiccup syntax directly in EDN files, and why you might want to."

 :content
 [:article

  [:p "Instead of Markdown, you can write posts directly in "
   [:strong "Hiccup"] " — Clojure's HTML DSL expressed as plain data."]

  [:p "Because Hiccup vectors are valid EDN, post files are pure data. "
   "The generator loads them with " [:code "clojure.edn/read-string"] ", "
   "so no code is ever evaluated. It is safe, simple, and composable."]

  [:h2 "A quick example"]

  [:p "Here is a Clojure snippet you might embed in a post:"]

  [:pre
   [:code
    "(defn square [x]\n  (* x x))\n\n(square 7) ;; => 49"]]

  [:h2 "Why bother?"]

  [:ul
   [:li [:strong "Full HTML control"] " — use any element or attribute directly."]
   [:li [:strong "No parsing ambiguity"] " — it is data all the way down."]
   [:li [:strong "Composable"] " — share fragments across posts as EDN values (future work)."]]

  [:h2 "When to prefer Markdown"]

  [:p "Markdown wins for prose-heavy posts where you want clean source text "
   "that is easy to read without rendering. Use Hiccup when you need "
   "precise layout, custom elements, or structured content that Markdown "
   "would mangle."]

  [:p "Both formats produce the same internal post map; the site generator "
   "treats them identically from that point on."]]}
